# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1780 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 5, 1780.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] It resulted in the re-election of Thomas Chittenden to a one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Bennington on October 12.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont House of Representatives appointed a committee to examine the votes of the freemen of Vermont for governor, lieutenant governor, treasurer, and members of the governor's council.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Thomas Chittenden was re-elected governor.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Benjamin Carpenter was re-elected lieutenant governor, and Ira Allen was re-elected as treasurer.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The names of candidates and balloting totals were not recorded.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1781 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 4, 1781.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Charlestown, New Hampshire on October 12.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The meeting site was chosen as part of a short-lived effort to create a union of Vermont with 17 Connecticut River Valley towns of New Hampshire.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont House of Representatives appointed a committee to examine the votes of the freemen of Vermont for governor, lieutenant governor, treasurer, and governor's council members.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The popular vote indicated that no candidate for lieutenant governor had received a majority.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In keeping with the Vermont Constitution, the choice fell to the Vermont General Assembly, which chose Elisha Payne, a New Hampshire resident who supported the union of New Hampshire's western towns with Vermont.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1782 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 3, 1782.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Manchester on October 10.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Thomas Chittenden was re-elected to a one-year term as governor.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In keeping with the Vermont Constitution, the choice fell to the Vermont General Assembly, which chose Paul Spooner for a one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Ira Allen was re-elected to a one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1783 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 2, 1783.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Westminster on October 9.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, Paul Spooner was re-elected to a second one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In addition, Ira Allen was re-elected to a one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1784 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 7, 1784.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Rutland on October 14.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the race for governor, Thomas Chittenden was re-elected to a one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, Paul Spooner was chosen for a third one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] No candidate for treasurer obtained a majority.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In accordance with the Vermont Constitution, the Vermont General Assembly was required to make a selection.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] On October 15, the Assembly (Vermont House of Representatives, governor, and governor's council) re-elected Ira Allen to a one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1785 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 6, 1785.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Windsor on October 13.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the race for governor, Thomas Chittenden was re-elected to a one-year term, his eighth.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, Paul Spooner was chosen for a fourth one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] On October 14, the Assembly (Vermont House of Representatives, governor, and governor's council) re-elected Ira Allen to his eighth one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1786 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 5, 1786.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Rutland on October 12.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the race for governor, Thomas Chittenden was re-elected to a one-year term, his ninth.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, no candidate received a majority.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] As required by the Vermont Constitution, the Vermont General Assembly convened on October 13 to make a choice.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The balloting by the Assembly resulted in the selection of Paul Spooner for a fifth one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Spooner subsequently declined the office.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] On October 14, the General Assembly selected Joseph Marsh, who began performing the duties in February 1787.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The election for treasurer also resulted in no candidate obtaining a majority.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] As with the lieutenant governor's office, the Vermont Constitution required the General Assembly to choose.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1786-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] On October 13, the Assembly chose Samuel Mattocks for treasurer, the first time since the republic's founding that Ira Allen was not selected.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] The **1808 Vermont gubernatorial election** took place on September 6, 1808.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] It resulted in the election of Isaac Tichenor to a one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Montpelier on October 13.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] The committee's examination of the votes showed that former Governor Isaac Tichenor defeated incumbent Israel Smith for a one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, the voters selected Paul Brigham for his thirteenth one-year term.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] Benjamin Swan was elected to a one-year term as treasurer, his ninth.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] In the races for lieutenant governor and treasurer, the vote totals and names of other candidates were not recorded.
[src:1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election/1808-vermont-gubernatorial-election] In the race for governor, a contemporary newspaper article reported the results as follows.
